# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-philadelphia-athletics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1901 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 5th in the American League with a record of 68–65.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and played at Oriole Park.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The **1901 Boston Americans season** was the first season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox, and the first season of play for the American League (AL).
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] It resulted in the Americans finishing second in the AL with a record of 79 wins and 57 losses, four games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] On February 11, Jimmy Collins, third baseman for the National League Boston Beaneaters became the first player under contract for the Boston Americans after being offered a contract of $4000 with the added ability to sign subsequent players to contracts.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Collins was joined on March 4 by the outfielder Chick Stahl, who was also from the Beaneaters.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Defecting with Stahl and Collins was the outfielder Buck Freeman.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Yet perhaps the most important signing was that of the 34 year old St.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis Cardinals pitcher Cy Young, who accepted a contract worth $3500 from the Boston Americans.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Vital to the signing of Cy Young from the Cardinals was the signing of Cy Young's catcher in St.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis, Lou Criger; the value that Young gave to Criger and that Criger gave to Young was so strong, that it is unlikely that Young would have signed for the Americans if Criger had not done so.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The total attendance for the Red Sox was 289,448, the second most in the American League (behind the White Sox' 354,350) and more than the crosstown Boston Beaneaters' 146,502.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 12 home runs and had 114 RBIs while recording a .339 batting average.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 38 complete games with a 33–10 record and 1.62 ERA, while striking out 158 in 371+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team had two games end in a tie; August 31 at Detroit Tigers and September 12 at Washington Senators.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Tied games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tied games are counted.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Cy Young led the league in ERA (1.62), shutouts (5; tied with Clark Griffith), strikeouts (158), and wins (33).
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1901 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 31st season of the franchise.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters finished fifth in the National League with a record of 69–69.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1901 Brooklyn Superbas** lost several players to the newly official major league, the American League.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas finished third in the National League with a record of 79–57.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The **1901 Chicago Orphans season** was the 30th season of the Chicago Orphans franchise, the 26th in the National League and the ninth at West Side Park.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The Orphans finished sixth in the National League with a record of 53–86.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The team was also known as the Remnants, due to many Orphans players leaving at the end of the 1900 season to join the upstart American League.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1901 Philadelphia Athletics season** involved the A's finishing fourth in the American League with a record of 74 wins and 62 losses.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The franchise that would become the modern Athletics originated in 1901 as a new franchise in the American League.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Western League had been renamed the American League in 1900 by league president Bancroft (Ban) Johnson, and declared itself the second major league in 1901.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Johnson created new franchises in the east and eliminated some franchises in the west.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia seems to have been a new franchise created to compete with the National League's Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Former catcher Connie Mack was recruited to manage the club.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Mack in turn persuaded Phillies minority owner Ben Shibe as well as others to invest in the team, which would be called the **Philadelphia Athletics**.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] He himself bought a 25 percent interest.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Nap Lajoie jumped from the Phillies to the crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, owned by Connie Mack.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie's batting average that year was .426, still a league record.
[src:1901-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The same year Lajoie became the second major leaguer to be intentionally walked with the bases loaded after Abner Dalrymple in 1881.
